The Blackstone Hotel is not only a legend in Chicago, it's a unique blend of classic architecture & modern design. Sweeping views of Lake Michigan, easy to get to, attentive staff, clean and chic; the tower brings the city to life. Creativity with the touch of a whimsical historical charm, that's the ticket. theblackstonehotel

The overall vibe is so dynamic. You could be here for business, or on a Chicago getaway like us. Both would fit. I mean, the Presidential Suite has actually hosted presidents! Good enough for a President? Good enough for me. Wait, not just good... great! We are obsessed.

What a stunning experience! Highly recommend @esme_chicago for a unique Chicago dining excursion. ‚≠êÔ∏è

@esme_chicago // In the beautiful streets of Chicago‚Äôs Lincoln Park neighborhood lies a simple sign that leads to a magnificent dining experience with a Michelin star ‚≠êÔ∏è. Chef Jenner Tomaska and wife and partner Katrina Bravo opened fine-dining restaurant Esm√© in 2021.  With the goal to integrate art, philanthropy, and stunningly elegant food, they created a tasting menu (that changes quarterly) that expresses their shared vision as a community-focused, impact-driven restaurant.

First, you are greeted with a ‚Äúcocktail hour‚Äù inspired  table with a snack and a glass of champagne.  There, you learn about the art, history, and what to expect of your 3 hour dining experience at Esm√©.

Next, you are escorted to your table.  You have a specific server, but you meet several others throughout the night.  The whole group is serving together with no hierarchy, all a team!

For this season‚Äôs menu, the restaurant is giving a percentage of the ticket proceeds back to the schools that inspired the dishes for the meal.  Pretty amazing, right?

Together, you lean on honesty with yourselves and each other to help get you through difficult moments and you support each other whenever old pain needs attention. Ingredients:

1/4 cup grated parm cheese
1/2 tsp salt
1/2 tsp garlic powder
1/2 tbsp Italian seasoning

Recipe:
üèàCut cheese sticks in half 
üèàIn a small bowl beat 1 egg
üèàIn a plastic bag add Italian seasoning, parm cheese, almond flour, garlic powder, and salt
üèàMix Seasonings
üèàDip cheese sticks in egg then coat in season mixture 
üèàPlace in freezer for 1 hour 
üèàIn large skillet or Wok pour olive oil

Let‚Äôs talk about an issue that I‚Äôve noticed at theme parks.
Yesterday I posted about Lennox finally being tall enough for Unikitty Disco Drop @legolandcalifornia 

This ride has a height requirement of 40‚Äù. Which she met every single time she was measured over a 4 day trip. 

Yet, when we attempted to ride Dragon which is also a 40‚Äù height requirement we were turned away as she clearly was not tall enough when being measured. 

This is not unique to Legoland. In fact, this ride in this reel is at @disneyland California Adventure. It also has a 40‚Äù height requirement, she also does not reach the measurement for it. 

There‚Äôs two main issues with theme park height requirements 

1. Legoland does not measure prior to getting in line, so for the instance of the Dragon we made it all the way through before we found out she wasn‚Äôt tall enough and we had to exit. (Talk about a disappointed little girl) 

2. Inconsistency in what they use to measure. 3 different rides, all the same height requirement, all different measurements. (Jumping Jellyfish at DCA also has a 40‚Äù requirement and measures different from Symphony Swings). 

When you have a child who is at the cusp of a new height requirement grouping, the inconsistency in measuring makes it difficult to prepare your child that they may not be able to ride. I‚Äôm a firm believer in not trying to fudge your child‚Äôs height to get on a ride, I don‚Äôt even attempt if I know they aren‚Äôt tall enough. But this time of inconsistency makes that hard.

Lennox did her first 40‚Äù ride this past weekend! For those of you that go to theme parks, you know how big of a deal it is to finally hit 40‚Äù. It unlocks a whole new group of rides!

And when you‚Äôre surrounded by plastic sheeting and you can‚Äôt find anything because everything is in a strange place, and construction goes on until 2am every night, it really starts to wear on you!üòù

We‚Äôre so close to the finish line, almost three months in, and realizing we still can only control what we can control. 

Pushing as much as we can push, and also knowing when to not push too far. As much as I want my house put put back together, I also want everything done right. 

So I did my daily practice this morning, had a good cry lol, got re-centered, and  I‚Äôm back:) We got this! 

Thx for following along and to all of you who have been so supportive. 1,000 percent first world problems I‚Äôm venting about (just wanted to acknowledge that:)

We are raising tree hugging, flower sniffing, animal kissing, planet loving, dirt worshipping free thinkers and proud of it.

What kind of children are you raising?

The internet is filled with reminders lately that we ‚Äòonly have 18 summers with our kids.‚Äô But we are also often reminded that we should be doing everything we can to prepare our littles ones for middle school and our middle schoolers for high school and our high schoolers for college...

These two messages seem very contradicting to me. How can we slow things down and let kids be kids if we are also supposed to be making sure they are doing everything they can to be the best college admission applicants?

I do believe preparing my children for the future is important. But I also believe that one of the best gifts I can give my children is the freedom to have a fun, tree-climbing, ocean-jumping, wild and free childhood so when they are old enough to have start making big decisions like what careers they want to pursue, they will have had the time and freedom to explore their passions and interests enough to know what path they want to choose.

We believe that maybe some of the preparation children need is to have fun and carefree days now so they will have a good, happy foundation to start adulthood with.

We believe that our children‚Äôs childhoods should be filled with adventures and exploration, not just 18 years of memorizing facts and always preparing for the next stage for 9 months of the year. The reality is that parents might not feel so much pressure to live up the summer months if we did not feel we had to spend the rest of the months rushing from sports activities to music lessons to scouts with little time to just enjoy just being together as a family.

Sleeping on your back in pregnancy.  What have you heard? 

Your body will likely shift to the side if you fall asleep on your back later in pregnancy.  And don‚Äôt freak out if you have slept on your back.

Let‚Äôs chat laboring down. 

There has been a lot of recent studies on this topic.  Some state that there is no benefit to delaying pushing once the patient is completely dilated. 

I agree that if the patient is just lying and not moving to help facilitate rotation, then laboring down and just waiting for contractions to push baby out probably won‚Äôt work.  BUT, if a baby is still high in the pelvis, then helping mom get into other positions to help bring baby down, imo definitely helps with descent. 

The key is to make sure that you are being actively managed in labor.  In other words, your nurse should be moving you side to side and utilizing the peanut ball to help baby rotate.  If your nurse isn‚Äôt doing that, make sure to ask your support person to help.

Let‚Äôs talk about why jewelry fit and sizing is so important. This client came to me for a septum piercing (which turned out so cute! Love the blue opal) during the piercing I inquired after the scar on her nostril. 
.
Many years ago she had a hoop installed in a still fresh nostril piercing. This hoop was too thin, and too snug. And the piercing was still healing- and having swelling. Despite it not being very painful, it began migrating through her nose. By the time she realized the damage it was causing and removed it, the scarring was already permanent. Now years later she forgets the scar is even there (and we have a cute new septum to focus on!)
.
But this is why quality, safe, properly fitted jewelry is so important. It may seem like ‚Äújust a piercing‚Äù or ‚Äújust a piece of jewelry‚Äù. But it could be a scar you‚Äôll carry forever. Thankfully this clients scarring was minimal, but this could have easily been much worse. Please take good care of your body and your piercings. 
.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Find the right contact: The social media team isn‚Äôt always the same as the partnerships team- scour LinkedIn, brand websites, press releases, Instagram and Google for the right person.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Put your best foot forward: Include your media kit with- your personal story, audience data, previous campaigns/brands you‚Äôve worked with and collaboration options (for example: reels/stories)

Let me explain: I‚Äôve heard it said that ‚ÄúWe all have the same 24 hours in a day!‚Äù

And I have to kindly disagree! This quote in its varying forms, is meant to be motivational‚Ä¶.

And it is. Every time I read it I feel motivated to DO MORE. Even Beyonc√© only has 24 hours in a day, right?

And yes, these quotes can help inspire us to do more- but they can also be damaging. Causing us to compare to others.

While it‚Äôs true that Beyonc√© does have the same 24 hours as myself, our 24 hours are NOT the same! 

I do not have a team of assistants & all that comes with being the queen B!! If I did, then my 24 hours would most likely look vastly different to how they currently do.

My day will also look different to that of a wealthy single bachelor, a single parent, someone without any support system, someone who has an entire team working their business, etc etc!!

It is true that if you prioritize the important tasks, if you sacrifice certain things like watching Netflix every evening, you can achieve more.

We all have the capability to work towards our goals if we organize our time & prioritize and make some sacrifices.

But please know that if you are struggling, or want to watch Netflix, you are NOT failing!!! 

At the moment, I am trying to run my business from home while having a chronic illness & learning to walk on my own. Between physical therapy, infusions, and other appointments. This means that I‚Äôm not able to do as much as I would like.

I could work through til 2 am, however I‚Äôm not sure this would be if any benefit to anyone, especially myself. 

Some things that happen during your day will be choices you make, like choosing to spend your evening having quality time with your partner/family instead of working.

Things like caring for your children, cleaning your home, cooking etc are not things you can choose not to do without neglecting your responsibilities.

Our use of those 24 hours will all be different depending on our circumstances. We all do have 24 hours in a day. But we DO NOT have the same 24 hours!

We saw deer and squirrels.
And we got to camp ate some tasty Mountain House and went straight to bed!

Being in my 20s I know I have more freedom and less responsibility then I will have later in life. 
But no matter what I will always keep my youthful energy. I wanna be that 80 year old woman dancing barefoot in the park with her husband. Or that 40 year old laughing so hard she‚Äôs cries at the wine bar with her friends. Or that 30 year old hosting game nights and corn hole competitions. I want to live and feel everything always. So yeah I guess I do want to be forever young.

All in all it was an insane experience and my favorite part of Yosemite.

üçÇ Pumpkin Chocolate Chips Bars - SAVE this recipe! üòç

My daughter helped me make these and said it was the best treat I ever made - this was even after she watched me tweak my old recipe to make them ‚Äúhealthier‚Äù üôåüèª 

We also had a house full of 5th grade boys who tried them and I think they would have eaten the whole pan if I let them üòÇ They are gooey and DELICIOUS and AMAZING. ‚§µÔ∏è

1 cup unsalted organic butter, room temperature
3/4 cup coconut sugar
3/4 cup honey
1 egg
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
1 cup canned pumpkin puree
2 cups white whole wheat flour
1 tablespoon pumpkin pie spice
1 teaspoon baking soda
3/4 teaspoon salt
1 package (12 oz) semisweet chocolate chips

Preheat oven to 350 degrees and spray a 9√ó13 baking sheet with non-stick cooking spray. In the bowl of a stand mixer, cream butter and coconut sugar and honey until smooth. Add egg and vanilla and beat until combined. Mix in pumpkin puree.

Combine the flour, pumpkin pie spice, baking soda and salt in a small bowl. On low speed, mix dry ingredients into wet until just combined. Fold in chocolate chips.

Spread batter evenly in pan and bake until a toothpick inserted in the center comes out almost clean, about 30-35 minutes. Cool completely in pan. Cut into 24 squares.

Easiest chicken noodle soup EVER with a secret ingredient‚Ä¶

SOY SAUCE! üòç

Or coconut aminos in my case - they are interchangeable. Believe me when I tell you, it makes the broth SO flavorful and delicious! 

This soup is so good, it‚Äôs super easy and my kids LOVE it. Win-win-win! üôåüèª Sharing the recipe because it‚Äôs such a good, healthy dinner for a busy weeknight. 

Quick + Easy Chicken Noodle Soup 
- 1¬†tablespoon¬†of olive oil
- 1/2 cup - 1 cup diced frozen onion
- 3¬†cloves¬†of garlic¬†minced (I use from a jar)
- 5¬†carrots¬†peeled and sliced into 1/2 inch pieces
- 2¬†celery sticks¬†sliced into 1/2 inch pieces
- 1 whole cooked rotisserie chicken, shredded
- 3¬†tablespoon¬†of soy sauce or coconut aminos
- 12¬†cups¬†of low sodium chicken broth
- 6¬†ounces¬†of extra wide egg noodles
- Sea salt and freshly ground pepper

Instructions
1. Add olive oil to a large pot and heat over medium-high heat. (I actually used my #instantpot on the saut√© function because it‚Äôs such a big pot).‚Ä®
2. Add onions and cook until they start to soften and become translucent, 2-3 minutes.‚Ä®
3. Add garlic, carrots and celery and saute for another few minutes.‚Ä®
4. Add chicken broth, soy sauce, 2 teaspoons of salt and several turns of freshly ground pepper. Bring to a boil. ‚Ä®
5. Stir in egg noddles and chicken and let cook according to the directions on the egg noodles.‚Ä®
6. Adjust salt and pepper to taste.

30 Kinda Hard is a 30-day challenge where we will commit to our health and create new habits through the following:

3. Drink 1 gallon of water each day. 

4. Stick to one of our flexible, live-your-life nutrition plans. Again, we will find the one perfect for you!

5. 10 minutes of personal development each day. You can listen to a podcast or read a book. I'll even have a list of recommendations.
